Europe Needs to Restart Its Migration Policy
Brussels—More than 900 migrants who tried to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
Meanwhile, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking have been searching all summer for safe harbors where their passengers can disembark.
Refugee and migrant camps on the Greek island of Lesbos are overcrowded, and other camps in Libya are in similarly bad condition.
Turkey has torn up the 2016 agreement aimed at preventing migrants from entering the EU.
Although Europe wants to help migrants and respects international law, it does not want to be overcrowded.
Between 2015 and 2016, the number of refugees and migrants entering the EU surged — many of them fleeing the war in Syria — which greatly affected trust within the EU.
The massive influx of migrants eroded governments' confidence in the EU's external borders and asylum management, and also highlighted the futility of cooperation with countries of origin.
As a result, migration has become a political football, a favorite of populists.
Under President Ursula von der Leyen's leadership, the new European Commission must regain control of the migration issue while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
To this end, the EU needs to reestablish policies in four areas and mobilize member states to act in Europe's interest.
First, the EU must urgently secure its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping its internal borders open.
Countries where people can freely move internally, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, would never outsource control of their external borders to a state or region.
Controlling the EU's external borders must be a collective task and also a national task.
The EU Border and Coast Guard Agency Frontex must be further strengthened and should be deployed with joint security forces by member states — including coastlines and airports.
The EU must also restart Operation Sophia, targeting illegal migration in the Mediterranean.
Second, Europe needs to treat economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Mixing them together has brought the asylum system to the brink of collapse; treating them separately helps ensure that migrants concerned about their safety can voice their concerns with their rights protected.
Addressing the EU's real economic and social needs requires an effective blue card or green card policy targeting economic migrants, along with the implementation of an overall immigration target.
This must not be left until the next migration crisis to consider introducing these mechanisms.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
First, the number of economic immigrants entering the EU labor market must be recognized as a matter of common interest.
Second, policies must clearly define which immigrants are welcome.
Third, member states must answer what EU assistance is needed to ensure a smooth immigration process.
Finally, visas and work permits must be put on the table to facilitate the return of illegal immigrants to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaties, member states need to manage immigrants coming from outside the EU themselves.
However, if governments reach an agreement on an overall EU immigration target, it will be a major step forward.
In return, member states can specify the source countries and specific requirements for economic migrants they want, as well as the EU budget resources needed to accommodate them.
In this way, the right to accept immigrants would become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long implemented a proactive immigration policy, selecting immigrants based on criteria such as country of origin, skills, and age.
Europe can do the same as well.
Third, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First, the one-size-fits-all requirement for the mandatory redistribution of asylum seekers within the EU must be abandoned.
This requirement undermines the atmosphere within the EU, but it could still be feasible if the border, asylum, and immigration systems are fully effective.
Additionally, it cannot be expected that the EU's frontline member states alone will solve the issue of illegal migrants crossing external borders.
Camp accommodation has become overcrowded, and migrants suffer abuse by authorities or are driven northward.
The responsibility of the first EU member state that migrants arrive in must be reinforced by EU solidarity.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to streamline the behavior and management capabilities of national asylum agencies.
Only in this way can national decisions be respected throughout the Schengen area, ensuring the integrity of the cross-border travel zone.
After streamlining the behavior and management capabilities of national asylum agencies, the asylum application processing procedures can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should build stronger win-win cooperation with countries of origin and transit countries.
These links are crucial in order to repatriate migrants who are legally prohibited from entering the EU back to their countries of origin.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all foreign policy tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as programs in areas such as security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's immigration targets, as well as skill cooperation aimed at preparing for European job positions, can be offered to third countries eager to receive stable remittances.
At the same time, the EU must address the root causes of migration.
This includes the population explosion in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and a lack of job opportunities.
The EU's aid should focus on reshaping stability and reducing risks through support for security, community resilience, and good governance.
Success in this area can make investments safer, unlock private and domestic finance, thereby achieving national economic growth, job creation, and providing alternatives to migration.
The new European Commission has the opportunity to move the EU away from instinctive reactions to immigration crises and toward a more coherent and sustained approach, both internally and externally.
We must not miss this opportunity.
